{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651512"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:24:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:24:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18469"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18469"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[1,0,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11198"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114215"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11198"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96215"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4900"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6640"},{"type":"tags","id":"6641"},{"type":"tags","id":"6648"},{"type":"tags","id":"9842"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26020"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114215"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe heart contains four chambers and four valves that work to ensure unidirectional blood flow. Understanding the normal flow of blood through these chambers is essential for comprehending cardiac physiology.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal flow of blood through the cardiac chambers?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right atrium to right ventricle to pulmonary artery","Left ventricle to left atrium to aorta","Right ventricle to right atrium to pulmonary artery","Left atrium to right atrium to right ventricle","Right atrium to left atrium to left ventricle"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence is \u003Cstrong\u003Eright atrium to right ventricle to pulmonary artery\u003C/strong\u003E. Blood returns into the right atrium from the systemic circulation via the superior and inferior venae cavae. It then enters the right ventricle through the tricuspid valve and is pumped through the pulmonary valve into the pulmonary artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricle to left atrium to aorta\u003C/strong\u003E describes an impossible sequence as the mitral valve prevents backward flow from left ventricle to left atrium. \u003Cstrong\u003ERight ventricle to right atrium to pulmonary artery\u003C/strong\u003E similarly describes backward flow that is prevented by the tricuspid valve. \u003Cstrong\u003ELeft atrium to right atrium to right ventricle\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eright atrium to left atrium to left ventricle\u003C/strong\u003E both describe direct flow between the atria, which cannot occur in a normal heart due to the interatrial septum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cardiac valves ensure unidirectional blood flow through the heart chambers. The atrioventricular valves (tricuspid and mitral) prevent backflow from ventricles to atria during ventricular contraction, while the semilunar valves (pulmonary and aortic) prevent backflow from the great vessels into the ventricles during ventricular relaxation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Blood flows from the right atrium to right ventricle through the tricuspid valve, then to pulmonary artery through the pulmonary valve.","Blood flows from the left atrium to left ventricle through the mitral valve, then to aorta through the aortic valve.","The cardiac valves ensure unidirectional blood flow by preventing backflow between chambers."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u0022Heart Valves NIH\u0022 by National Heart Lung and Blood Institute (NIH) is under Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Heart_valves_NIH.jpg\u003E","Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur A. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96215"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18469"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21381"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21381"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/AGhX2xEv5MrvLZT1p0KtY6pNM32HJE.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/AGhX2xEv5MrvLZT1p0KtY6pNM32HJE.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":441}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96215"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T13:34:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T13:35:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11198"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114215"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for 